1 Inbred Mouse Strains

We start off with over 1000 mouse samples measured at the TOMCAT beamline of the Swiss Light Source at the Paul Scherrer Institute in Villigen, Switzerland. Each sample consists of 14GB of image data as well as 98 genetic tags correlating each sample and phenotype to a specific pattern of inheritance.

2 Load the data in

Once the Spark Cluster has been created and you have the SparkContext called sc (automatically provided in Databricks Cloud or Zeppelin), the data can be loaded using the Spark Image Layer. The command readImage[Float] loads in the data as floating point images. The * indicates the all folders should be included which in this case means over 1000 samples. The command can easily read mega-, giga-, even petabytes of data from Amazons S3, Hadoop Filesystem (HDFS), or any shared / network filesystem.

val uctImages = 
    sc.readImage[Float]("s3n://bone-images/f2-study/*/ufilt.tif").cache

We can then move the data into a virtual database so instead of writing Scala code we can utilize easy SQL commands for further analysis.

uctImages.registerAsImageTable("ImageTable")

Although we execute the commands on only one machine, the data will be evenly loaded over all of the machines in the cluster (or cloud). The cache suffix keeps the files in memory so they can be read faster as many of our image processing tasks access the images a number of times.

3 Image Processing

Once the table has been registered we can perform our analysis using SQL or Scala depending on which commands are easier or more flexible for the given analysis. The next steps are a typical analysis process for extracting the porosity data from the images and analyzing the cells inside.

3.1 Image Enhancement

Since the measurements have some degree of noise from the detectors, we first clean up the images using a Gaussian Filter.

SELECT sample,gaussianFilter(image) INTO FilteredImages FROM ImageTable

3.2 Segmentation

To segment the images into bone and air, we can either manually specify a cut-off or simply use an automated approach like Otsu, IsoData, or Intermodes.

SELECT sample,applyThreshold(image,OTSU) INTO ThresholdImages FROM FilteredImages

3.3 Mask Creation and Porosity Extraction

From the segmented image, we can extract the cells by first creating a mask with all of the holes filled in.

SELECT sample, convexHullFillHoles(image) INTO MaskImages FROM ThresholdImages
SELECT sample, peelMask(thr.Image,mask.Image) INTO CorticalImage FROM ThreshImage thr 
  INNER JOIN MaskImages mask ON thr.sample = mask.sample
SELECT sample,peelMask(invert(thr.image),mask.image) INTO BonePorosity FROM ThreshImage thr 
  INNER JOIN MaskImages mask ON thr.sample = mask.sample

3.4 Labeling Objects

We can then identify the individual cells using component labeling.

SELECT sample,componentLabel(image) INTO LabelImages FROM BonePorosity

3.5 Shape Analysis (Volume, Position, Shape)

Now we can calculate the shape information for the cell volume to look at some of the statistics. For this step we move back to Scala to keep things easier

// Run a shape analysis to measure the position, area, and intensity of each identified region
val cellLabels = LabelImages.toLabels()
val shapeAnalysis = EllipsoidAnalysis.runIntensityShapeAnalysis(cellLabels)

Once this analysis is done, we can move back to SQL and use standard commands for analyzing and visualizing all of the shapes

shapeAnalysis.toDF().registerTempTable("BoneAnalysis")

4.3 Viewing Individual Samples

The shape analysis from a single sample can easily be brought up and rendered in the browser.

SELECT lacuna_points FROM BoneAnalysis WHERE strain == "B6" & gender == "female" LIMIT 1

A number of further analyses can be made in both 2D and 3D plots looking at everything from cell size and shape to density.

SELECT lacuna_points FROM BoneAnalysis WHERE strain == "C3H" & gender == "female" LIMIT 1

4.4 Compare two datasets directly

val b6cells = sq.sql("SELECT lacuna_points FROM BoneAnalysis WHERE strain == 'B6' & gender == 'female'")
val c3cells = sq.sql("SELECT lacuna_points FROM BoneAnalysis WHERE strain == 'C3H' & gender == 'female')

(b6data ++ c3cells).groupBy("strain").show
